<p>
After spending years focusing on my career in robotics and I have reached a point where I have some money sitting in the bank and don't know what to do with it. I am writing this blog-post to share my notes on investing to help people who are starting off their journey in investing.
</p>

<div id="outline-container-org60e11da" class="outline-2">
<h2 id="org60e11da"><span class="section-number-2">1</span> Data Informed Approach</h2>
<div class="outline-text-2" id="text-1">
</div>
<div id="outline-container-orga6cfeb7" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="orga6cfeb7"><span class="section-number-3">1.1</span> Disclaimer</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-1-1">
<p>
Past data is not always an indicator of the future. In the words of Sean Ammirati, my professor at CMU, we need to be data informed and not data driven.
</p>
</div>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-org1a1557b" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="org1a1557b"><span class="section-number-3">1.2</span> Assumptions</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-1-2">
<p>
To keep the analysis simple and build intuition we will start with some assumptions which can relaxed later:
</p>
</div>
<div id="outline-container-org35078a3" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="org35078a3"><span class="section-number-4">1.2.1</span> The effects of inflation are canceled out by reinvesting the dividends</h4>
</div>
<div id="outline-container-org6b91c6a" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="org6b91c6a"><span class="section-number-4">1.2.2</span> We consider a fixed amount invested at a single start date rather than monthly investments</h4>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-org0604416" class="outline-2">
<h2 id="org0604416"><span class="section-number-2">2</span> Does the stock market grow exponentially?</h2>
<div class="outline-text-2" id="text-2">
</div>
<div id="outline-container-org03a054c" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="org03a054c"><span class="section-number-3">2.1</span> Stock Growth v.s. Compounding Interest</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-2-1">
<p>
When people talk about compounding interest, e.g. for the money you put in a bank, you get to re-invest your interest which generates more interest and the effects compound generating exponential returns just like the spread of corona-virus.
Does this make sense for stocks? If you sell a $100 stock at $110 you cannot re-invest your $10 profit back into the stock since you cannot buy it at $100 anymore! Of-course, you can re-invest the dividends but that's only ~2% for S&amp;P-500 which would require more that 35 years for your money to double.
Stock values grow exponentially through the growth of their business. Imagine that you invested in a restaurant business which requires $1 million to start 1 restaurant. Once the business earns $1 million dollars from profits of the first restaurant it can start a 2nd one. This will allow them to make $2 million dollars in the same time using which they can start 2 more restaurant which would then scale to 4, 8, 16, 32 and keep growing exponentially!
</p>


<div class="figure">
<p><img src="./obipy-resources/9nilbq.png" alt="9nilbq.png" />
</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-org846c710" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="org846c710"><span class="section-number-3">2.2</span> Take-away</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-2-2">
<p>
Market growth is exponential and it is very important to enter it early. The difference could cost you 8x as opposed to 16x returns.
</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-orga434ed0" class="outline-2">
<h2 id="orga434ed0"><span class="section-number-2">3</span> How sensitive are the returns to investment timing?</h2>
<div class="outline-text-2" id="text-3">

<div class="figure">
<p><img src="./obipy-resources/AbXLTW.png" alt="AbXLTW.png" />
</p>
</div>

<p>
Growth factor is the ratio of the return while exiting the market to the amount invested during entry.
</p>
</div>
<div id="outline-container-orgc3b6435" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="orgc3b6435"><span class="section-number-3">3.1</span> Market Entry</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-3-1">
</div>
<div id="outline-container-org51a7a09" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="org51a7a09"><span class="section-number-4">3.1.1</span> How does the growth factor change for different start dates and a fixed investment period?</h4>
<div class="outline-text-4" id="text-3-1-1">

<div class="figure">
<p><img src="./obipy-resources/TVFW9U.png" alt="TVFW9U.png" />
</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-org0a23da1" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="org0a23da1"><span class="section-number-4">3.1.2</span> Take-aways</h4>
<div class="outline-text-4" id="text-3-1-2">
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>Start times can effect the returns but as we'll see in the next section, in the long run this doesn't matter.</li>
<li>Strategies like dollar-cost averaging (distributing investments into smaller chunks over a period of time instead of investing in one-shot) can be used to mitigate this effect.</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-org3648d1a" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="org3648d1a"><span class="section-number-3">3.2</span> Investment Period</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-3-2">
</div>
<div id="outline-container-org4b00c8c" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="org4b00c8c"><span class="section-number-4">3.2.1</span> How does the growth factor change for different investment periods and a given start date?</h4>
<div class="outline-text-4" id="text-3-2-1">

<div class="figure">
<p><img src="./obipy-resources/d1hS2F.png" alt="d1hS2F.png" />
</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-org3d023a1" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="org3d023a1"><span class="section-number-3">3.3</span> Take-aways</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-3-3">
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>It doesn't make sense to expect returns in the short-term, growth is exponential over a long-term.</li>
<li>In the long run, you should expect exponential returns but they can be sensitive to timing. Hence, it is a good strategy to invest a larger portion of your portfolio in bonds as you approach closer to retirement.</li>
</ul>

<p>
<b>"Time in the market is more important than timing the market"</b>
</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div id="outline-container-org901f335" class="outline-2">
<h2 id="org901f335"><span class="section-number-2">4</span> Other important take-aways</h2>
<div class="outline-text-2" id="text-4">
</div>
<div id="outline-container-org8fd58a9" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="org8fd58a9"><span class="section-number-3">4.1</span> It's not possible to time the market consistently for a long period of time</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-4-1">
<p>
[<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=w_aOERmUWdA&amp;feature=youtu.be">Ben Flix's Video</a>] talks about different studies that
</p>
</div>
</div>
<div id="outline-container-orgd411625" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="orgd411625"><span class="section-number-3">4.2</span> It's not possible to beat the market consistently for a long period of time</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-4-2">
<p>
Don't take my word, Warren Buffet placed a $1 million bet to any hedge fund who can beat the market for 10 years. Not surprising, he won the bet. See <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ibCMPzt01MA">this video from WSJ</a>
</p>
</div>
</div>
<div id="outline-container-orgebf697f" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="orgebf697f"><span class="section-number-3">4.3</span> Knowledge is different than information</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-4-3">
<p>
Many of these take-aways are easy to neglect when large hard-earned money is at stake. It's very common for investors give into emotions and follow-the-herd. When you see some friend bragging about investing in Tesla and Amazon at the right time. What they don't talk about is the other losses that they had to incur and for how long have they been able to sustain such perfect timings.
</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-orgc98492e" class="outline-2">
<h2 id="orgc98492e"><span class="section-number-2">5</span> Investing in your Career is better than time spent in active investing</h2>
<div class="outline-text-2" id="text-5">
<p>
Passive investment sets a VERY strong baseline that is really hard to beat by most active investors. Large hedge funds are out there trying to beat the market with a lot more resources than an individual part-time investor. Unless you have some special information that's very hard to get, the prices of the stocks would have already corrected to account for the information.
Time spent in active investing can be better used in learning new skills, taking courses, working on personal projects or startup/business.
You can scale you salary much faster and consistently than trying to beat the market!
</p>
</div>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-orgbeb5758" class="outline-2">
<h2 id="orgbeb5758"><span class="section-number-2">6</span> My Investment Strategy</h2>
<div class="outline-text-2" id="text-6">
</div>
<div id="outline-container-orge9088fb" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="orge9088fb"><span class="section-number-3">6.1</span> Consistent Long-term Passive Investing</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-6-1">
<p>
Save a fixed amount of money every month and consistently invest money in a diverse portfolio using index funds with low expense ratios [<a href="https://youtu.be/8I7hEKKw7qM">Rose's Video</a>]
</p>
</div>
</div>
<div id="outline-container-orgf6d8d4a" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="orgf6d8d4a"><span class="section-number-3">6.2</span> Set aside a speculation funds for active investing</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-6-2">
<p>
If you have strong cravings about trying to beat the market set aside a different fund ~5-20% of your portfolio which you are prepared to loose completely. As you realize how hard active investing is, you can scale it down to zero.
</p>
</div>
</div>
<div id="outline-container-org0cf7b08" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="org0cf7b08"><span class="section-number-3">6.3</span> Invest in yourself/career</h3>
</div>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-org6e7a0cf" class="outline-2">
<h2 id="org6e7a0cf"><span class="section-number-2">7</span> Other useful resources</h2>
<div class="outline-text-2" id="text-7">
</div>
<div id="outline-container-orgf466495" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="orgf466495"><span class="section-number-3">7.1</span> Which Investment Broker to use?</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-7-1">
<p>
Short answer: As of Aug 2020, Fidelity is the best option. See [<a href="https://youtu.be/gIVl79XAUXM">video</a>]
</p>
</div>
</div>
